  "time_ut": 1653965107,
  "original_lang": "si",
  "original_title": "\u0db6\u0dd0\u0d82\u0d9a\u0dd4 \u0d9a\u0dca\u0dc2\u0dda\u0dad\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dba\u0da7 \u0dc3\u0dc4\u0dcf\u0dba \u0dc0\u0dd3\u0db8\u0da7 \u0db8\u0dc4 \u0db6\u0dd0\u0d82\u0d9a\u0dd4\u0dc0\u0dd9\u0db1\u0dca \u0db1\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dcf\u0db8\u0db1\u0dba\u0d9a\u0dca",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "A regulation by the central bank to support the banking sector",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Considering the prevailing macroeconomic conditions and their impact on the banking sector, the Central Bank of Sri Lanka has decided to implement several regulatory measures to support the banking sector in providing credit flows to the economy and facilitating effective financial intermediation while maintaining the soundness of the banking sector.",
        "Basically, the Capital Conservation Buffer of 2.5% of the risk-weighted assets maintained by the licensed banks as an additional layer of capital to be utilized in times of need, is allowed to all the licensed banks to use in view of this prevailing situation. Also, the period until December 31, 2022 for licensed banks to meet the above capitalization requirements has been extended by one year to December 31, 2023, and accordingly, banks that are unable to meet the minimum capital requirements by the end of this year should merge with suitable financial institutions or be related to them. It has provided an opportunity to present its capital increase plans which include plans.",
        "In addition, licensed banks are encouraged to adopt an improved procedure for calculating capital adequacy ratio, and flexibility is given to licensed banks in using other comprehensive income for capital adequacy requirements in accordance with international standards. Also, as a short-term measure to help them adjust their liquidity levels, several other measures have been introduced, including flexibility to maintain the minimum liquidity coverage ratio and net stable funding ratio at 90% until 30 September 2022.",
        "Finally, the implementation of these policy measures by the licensed banks will be periodically reviewed by the Central Bank of Sri Lanka, and the concessions will be utilized by the licensed banks for the betterment of customers and the economy as a whole, while helping to maintain the resilience of the banking sector. It is further stated that the bank expects"
      ],
      "title_ents": [],
      "body_line_ents_list": [
        [
          {
            "text": "the Central Bank of Sri Lanka",
            "label": "ORG"
          }
        ],
        [
          {
            "text": "the Capital Conservation Buffer",
            "label": "LAW"
          },
          {
            "text": "2.5%",
            "label": "PERCENT"
          },
          {
